defaultpen(linewidth(.7pt)+fontsize(8pt));

dotfactor=4;

fill((0,-6)--(0,12)--(3,6)--cycle,gray);

draw((-2,0)--(4,0),Arrows(4));

draw((0,-7)--(0,13),Arrows(4));

draw((0,-6)--(3,6));

draw((0,12)--(3,6)); [/asy]

We draw a regular hexagon and one of its longest diagonals: [asy]
size(80);
draw((0,0)--(1,0)--(1.5,.5*sqrt(3))--(1,sqrt(3))--(0,sqrt(3))--(-.5,.5*sqrt(3))--cycle);
draw((1,0)--(0,sqrt(3)));
[/asy] Now we draw in the other two long diagonals.  We have split the hexagon into six equilateral triangles, which are congruent by symmetry.  [asy]
size(80);
draw((0,0)--(1,0)--(1.5,.5*sqrt(3))--(1,sqrt(3))--(0,sqrt(3))--(-.5,.5*sqrt(3))--cycle);
draw((1,0)--(0,sqrt(3))); draw((1.5,.5*sqrt(3))--(-.5,.5*sqrt(3))); draw((1,sqrt(3))--(0,0));
[/asy] We see that two side lengths make up one long diagonal.  Let the hexagon's side length be $s$, then, its long diagonal has length $2s$ and its perimeter has length $6s$.  The ratio of its long diagonal to its perimeter is hence $\frac{2s}{6s}=\boxed{\frac{1}{3}}$.

question:
What is the volume of a pyramid whose base is one face of a cube of side length $2$, and whose apex is the center of the cube? Give your answer in simplest form.

[asy]
import three;
triple A,B,C,D,EE,F,G,H;
A = (0,0,0);
B = (1,0,0);
C = (1,1,0);
D= (0,1,0);
EE = (0,0,1);
F = B+EE;
G = C + EE;
H = D + EE;
O = G/2;
draw(surface(B--O--C--cycle),red,nolight);
draw(surface(C--O--D--cycle),red+white,nolight);
draw(B--C--D);
draw(B--A--D,dashed);
draw(EE--F--G--H--EE);
draw(A--EE,dashed);
draw(B--F);
draw(C--G);
draw(D--H);
draw(A--O--C,dashed);
draw(B--O--D,dashed);
dot(A); dot(B); dot(C); dot(D); dot(EE); dot(F); dot(G); dot(H); dot(O);
[/asy]

solution:
The base of the pyramid is a square of side length $2$, and thus has area $2^2=4$. The height of the pyramid is half the height of the cube, or $\frac 12\cdot 2 = 1$. Therefore, the volume of the pyramid is \begin{align*}
\frac 13\cdot (\text{area of base})\cdot (\text{height}) &= \frac 13\cdot 4\cdot 1 \\
&= \boxed{\frac 43}.
\end{align*}

